\series bold 
Activity 1: Magnetic Forces on Moving Charges 
\layout Enumerate

Turn on the oscilloscope by pressing the power button.
 Turn the TIME/DIV knob completely counterclockwise.
 Adjust the INTEN (intensity) and FOCUS knobs so that a small bright spot
 is formed on the oscilloscope screen by the beam of electrons traveling
 toward you.
 Adjust the ILLUM (illumination) knob so that the grid on the screen can
 be seen clearly.
 Use the horizontal and vertical POSITION controls to center the spot on
 the screen.
\layout Enumerate


\series bold 
Note
\series default 
: An oscilloscope is built around the principle of the cathode ray tube.
 It emits electrons from its back end.
 These are accelerated by a series of electrodes and focussed to strike
 a fluorescent screen at its front.
 The result is a visible trace identifying voltage as a function of time.
\layout Enumerate
\added_space_bottom 30mm 

\series bold 
Predictions
\series default 
: What, if anything, will happen to the spot on the screen if the north
 pole of a magnet is brought near the left side of the oscilloscope? What
 will happen if you do the same with the south pole? What about when each
 of the poles are brought near to the top? [Please do not touch the oscilloscope
 with the magnet.] 
\layout Enumerate
\added_space_bottom 20mm 
Bring the N-pole of a horizontal bar magnet near, but not touching, the
 left side of the oscilloscope case at the height of the spot.
 Record the direction of any deflection.
 Repeat with the S-pole.
\layout Enumerate
\added_space_bottom 20mm 
Bring the N-pole of a vertical bar magnet near, but not touching, the top
 of the oscilloscope cast just above the spot.
 Record the direction of any deflection.
 Repeat with the S-pole.
\layout Enumerate

Turn off the oscilloscope.
\layout Enumerate
\added_space_bottom 15mm 
Did the directions of deflections meet your expectations? Explain.
 
